<li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation conference">Giarrusso, Paolo G. (2013). "Reify your collection queries for modularity and speed!". <i>Proceedings of the 12th annual international conference on Aspect-oriented software development</i>. ACM. <a href="/wiki/ArXiv" title="ArXiv">arXiv</a>:<span class="plainlinks"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//arxiv.org/abs/1210.6284">1210.6284</a><span style="margin-left:0.1em"><img alt="Freely accessible" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/9px-Lock-green.svg.png" title="Freely accessible" width="9" height="14" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/14px-Lock-green.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/18px-Lock-green.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="813" /></span></span>. <q>Also known as pimp-my-library pattern</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AScala+%28programming+language%29&amp;rft.atitle=Reify+your+collection+queries+for+modularity+and+speed%21&amp;rft.aufirst=Paolo+G.&amp;rft.aulast=Giarrusso&amp;rft.btitle=Proceedings+of+the+12th+annual+international+conference+on+Aspect-oriented+software+development&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.genre=conference&amp;rft_id=info%3Aarxiv%2F1210.6284&amp;rft.pub=ACM&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-33"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation newsgroup">marc (November 11, 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://groups.google.com/forum/#!original/scala-user/tIWGHcvQqH8/jUmV9cMdRJIJ">"What is highest priority for Scala to succeed"</a>. <a href="/wiki/Usenet_newsgroup" title="Usenet newsgroup">Newsgroup</a>:&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="news:scala-user@googlegroups.com">scala-user@googlegroups.com</a> <span style="font-size:100%" class="error citation-comment">Check <code style="color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;">|newsgroup=</code> value (<a href="/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#bad_url" title="Help:CS1 errors">help</a>)</span>. <a href="/wiki/Usenet" title="Usenet">Usenet:</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="news:5383616.373.1321307029214.JavaMail.geo-discussion-forums@prmf13">5383616.373.1321307029214.JavaMail.geo-discussion-forums@prmf13</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">April 15,</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AScala+%28programming+language%29&amp;rft.au=marc&amp;rft.btitle=What+is+highest+priority+for+Scala+to+succeed&amp;rft.date=2011-11-11&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fgroups.google.com%2Fforum%2F%23%21original%2Fscala-user%2FtIWGHcvQqH8%2FjUmV9cMdRJIJ&amp;rft_id=news%3A5383616.373.1321307029214.JavaMail.geo-discussion-forums%40prmf13&amp;rft.pub=scala-user%40googlegroups.com&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://meta.stackexchange.com/questions/184514/should-we-enrich-or-pimp-scala-libraries">"Should we "enrich" or "pimp" Scala libraries?"</a>. <i>stackexchange.com</i>. June 17, 2013<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">April 15,</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AScala+%28programming+language%29&amp;rft.atitle=Should+we+%22enrich%22+or+%22pimp%22+Scala+libraries%3F&amp;rft.date=2013-06-17&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fmeta.stackexchange.com%2Fquestions%2F184514%2Fshould-we-enrich-or-pimp-scala-libraries&amp;rft.jtitle=stackexchange.com&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-35"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Implicit classes were introduced in Scala 2.10 to make method extensions more concise. This is equivalent to adding a method <code>implicit def IntPredicate(i: Int) = new IntPredicate(i)</code>. The class can also be defined as <code>implicit class IntPredicates(val i: Int) extends AnyVal { ... }</code>, producing a so-called <i>value class</i>, also introduced in Scala 2.10. The compiler will then eliminate actual instantiations and generate static methods instead, allowing extension methods to have virtually no performance overhead.</span></li>
